{{Infobox language |name=Gyámi |region=Sichuan |extinct=not attested since the 19th century |ref=<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mair|first1=Victor H.|authorlink1=Victor H. Mair|title=Two Non-Tetragraphic Northern Sinitic Languages a. Implications of the Soviet Dungan Script for Chinese Language Reform b. Who Were the Gyámi?|journal=Sino-Platonic Papers|date=May 1990|issue=18|url=http://sino-platonic.org/complete/spp018_dungan_gyami.pdf}}</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Varieties of Chinese|Chinese]] |fam3=[[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] |iso2=none |glotto=none }}
The '''Gyami''' ({{bo|t=རྒྱ་མི|s=Gyami}}, "[[Han Chinese]]") were a Han people of [[Sichuan]] at the foot of the [[Tibetan Plateau]] who were reported by [[Brian Houghton Hodgson]] in 1874.
According to Hodgson, who thought the Gyami descended from a Chinese military outpost, the Chinese considered the Gyami to be [[Qiangic languages#Obsolete names|Qiangic]] speakers, suggesting that they did not recognize them as Han Chinese and that they did not use [[Chinese characters]]. [[Victor H. Mair]] notes that what little is recorded of their speech indicates a degree of assimilation to local languages, but that it is clearly a variety of Mandarin.
